Investments worldwide A platform for the future: The investments of PCC     All investments that garner long-term success tend to have one thing in common: they are based on sound market knowledge and extensive experience. 
Such expertise is essential for the identification and exploitation of business potential. 
As a value-led management and investment company, we – the PCC Group – therefore focus our energies exclusively in those areas in which we are able to leverage our decades of experience and know-how acquisition. 
Hence we continuously develop investments with potential to generate new and sustainable value added, investments that will steadily increase the value of our enterprise to the benefit of our investors. 
PCC SE seeks to acquire projects and businesses that have growth potential, can be further developed and are thus able to generate their own value increase over the medium term. 
Creating value together: The investments of PCC PCC intensified and further expanded its capital expenditure programme in fiscal 2014. 
Through this investment offensive, we have succeeded in further strengthening our production and services portfolio while also creating a sustainable basis for future value creation. 
In 2014, group-wide capital expenditure increased by some 85%, from €53.5 million to €98.8 million. 
The focus of our expenditures was again our Chemicals division. 
Here we continue to drive forward the modernisation of our production facilities and the establishment of new capacities. 
In 2014, we succeeded in completing or greatly advancing a number of long-term investment projects – particularly in the Chlorine segment, the Renewable Energies business unit and the Logistics division. 
We also passed a number of other milestones in 2015, such as the switchover of our chlorine production technology, completed in spring, and commencement of construction of our highly advanced production plant for silicon metal in Iceland around the middle of the year. 
We have made particular progress in the Chlorine segment over the last two years with the construction of a production plant for MCAA (monochloroacetic acid) at our largest chemicals site in Brzeg Dolny (Poland). 
We expect it to have come on stream in the fourth quarter 2015. 
We were also able to complete the switchover of our chlor-alkali electrolysis capability to environmentally friendly and energy-efficient membrane technology in early 2015. 
Among other things, this has enabled us to cut emissions by 140,000 metric tons of CO2 per year. 
The Surfactants and Polyols segments have also enjoyed investment successes. 
At the beginning of 2014, PCC Exol SA concluded a long-term rental agreement with a company in the Philippines allowing the use of its chemical production facilities there for the manufacture of fatty alcohols, an important feedstock for surfactant production. 
This deal means that PCC Exol SA has secured a source of strategically important raw materials while also satisfying sustainability criteria, allowing it to address new customer groups. 
At the beginning of 2014, PCC SE started talks with a Thai polyols manufacturer with a view to expanding our own Polyols operation. 
These negotiations culminated in January 2015 with the successful signing of an agreement to form the 50/50 joint venture IRPC-PCC Company Ltd. headquartered in Bangkok. 
Our objective here is to develop the rapidly growing markets of South-East Asia, China and India for our Chemicals division, and particularly our Polyols segment. 
Back at the beginning of April 2014, moreover, PCC SE acquired a site together with office buildings and a production facility in Essen, Germany. 
These assets were assigned to a newly founded subsidiary, PCC Prodex GmbH which is wholly owned by PCC Prodex Sp. 
z o.o., Warsaw (Poland). 
The purpose of this move is to establish a polyurethane systems manufacturing and marketing capability at the site. 
The Essen operation is to serve the German-speaking region and the Benelux markets. 
Within the Consumer Products segment, PCC Consumer Products Kosmet Sp. 
z o.o. continued the process started in 2014 of expanding and modernising its production facilities. 
This work is also due for completion in 2015, with the ensuing profits contributing to the Group’s finances. 
Within the Logistics division, we are investing in expanding the handling capacities of our container terminals. 
We recommissioned our newly upgraded terminal in Frankfurt (Oder) with an inauguration ceremony in December 2014 and have also made good progress with the expansion of similar facilities in Kutno (Central Poland) and Brzeg Dolny. 
Our Renewable Energies business unit likewise achieved investment successes, particularly in the Republic of Macedonia. 
One power plant there was connected to the grid back in 2013, with three further facilities following in 2014 and construction of a fifth expected to commence in 2015. 
We were also able to take forward our projects managed under the Holding/Projects segment. 
Thus, construction activities for our silicon metal production facility planned for Iceland began in June 2015. 
The financing of this project, which represents an investment outlay of around US$ 300 million (approx. EUR 265 million), has been secured, predominantly through a loan granted by KfW IPEX-Bank based in Frankfurt am Main, with further funds being provided by Icelandic co-investors. 
This project will be aided by tax concessions in Iceland and, from the German side, by a federal guarantee granted in recognition of the importance of the project for securing an important source of raw materials. 
Indeed, purchase agreements have already been concluded with German companies for the silicon metal to be produced in the future. 
In addition, we are also planning construction in the longer term of a plant for the manufacture of high-purity dimethyl ether (DME) in Russia.
